		<div class="post" id="post-4341126">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4341126)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4341126">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/qntm" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(571081); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=571081&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227484" alt="qntm" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=571081)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/qntm" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(571081); return false;" >qntm</a></span> <span class="odate time_1566864905 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">27 Aug 2019 00:15</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4341126">
									

<p>Good grief, this chapter.</p>
<p>Right, so, here's what happened.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>As I was beginning work on <em><a href="/antimemetics-division-hub">Five Five Five Five Five</a></em>, user sirpudding began writing a series of side-story Tales called <em><a href="/antimemetics-division-hub">What The Dead Know</a></em>, about Mobile Task Force ω-0, &quot;Ará Orún&quot; (&quot;Citizens of Heaven&quot;). We collaborated fairly closely and those Tales adhere impressively closely to the storyline I had worked out for <em>Five Five Five Five Five</em>. He stopped writing after <em><a href="/a-thin-dangerous-line">A Thin Dangerous Line</a></em>, because our intent was that the next chapter of those Tales, which is also this chapter of <em>Five Five Five Five Five</em>, would merge the two storylines. Marion Wheeler would have ascended into the noösphere upon her death in <em><a href="/your-last-first-day">Your Last First Day</a></em> &#8212; brain-damaged &#8212; and in this chapter she would meet Adam Wheeler one final time before dying for the absolutely final time. Then, ω-0 would present Adam Wheeler with his mission to find Bart Hughes, and the main storyline would continue.</p>
<p>What happened then is that a year passed. I'm a slow writer at the best of times and the story of <em>Five Five Five Five Five</em> became more complex than I planned it to, and produced some derails. (For example, the entire chapter <em><a href="/immemorial">Immemorial</a></em> wasn't originally planned.) In that time, user sirpudding disappeared, leaving his Tales incomplete, which is always regrettable. This is one of several reasons why I'm unlikely to collaborate directly with other writers on a single story again. I don't want to be the bottleneck. It sucks for <em>them</em>.</p>
<p>So, when I finally got here, my intention was to do those contributions justice, closing off the ω-0 storyline in a thematically meaningful way. (Without closing the door to all possible future ω-0 stories. It's generally bad manners to directly murder another writer's characters without their permission.) I wanted to explain what ω-0 had been up to all this time, why they hadn't intervened up until now and why they were intervening now and why they were going to be absent and unhelpful for the remainder of <em>Five Five Five Five Five</em>. Already that's a challenge. Sure, just <em>saying</em> what happened is fine. I can do that in a few paragraphs. Making a meaningful and legible story about it takes ten times more effort.</p>
<p>Next I had to figure out how Adam Wheeler would interact with ω-0 when it came down to it. I decided that only one character from ω-0 would speak to him, for simplicity &#8212; a last known survivor. And, because I was nervous about lifting existing characters from the <em>What The Dead Know</em> Tales, and none of them entirely suited the purpose to which I wanted to put them or gave me enough creative flexibility, I decided to create someone new. So I picked the surname &quot;Ulrich&quot; and went from there. And suddenly I had a serious problem. Because now I needed a story for this Ulrich person. A backstory, motivation, dreams, personality, an arc, a first name. A reason to care about Marion Wheeler! This requirement blindsided me. I had nothing prepped for it. I actually found it inordinately difficult to actually care about this new character who basically had a walk-on role to give Adam Wheeler some information and then end up dead.</p>
<p>There followed probably about two months of me earnestly attempting to turn this chapter into <em>the Daisy Ulrich experience</em>. I went through several iterations of her. At one point she was a civilian train driver who got roped into the Foundation during some crazy containment operation in the Channel Tunnel &#8212; but I decided that was too far back to start, and in any case the Foundation shouldn't be making a habit of hiring random civilians. At one point I had some content with her and Marion Wheeler serving as field agents alongside one another &#8212; Marion being Daisy's mentor &#8212; before Daisy joined a (physical reality) Mobile Task Force while Wheeler switched to the command track. At another point she was a neuroscientist who had joined the Foundation under mundane circumstances, or in order to escape an unpleasant &quot;real life&quot;&#8230; only to discover that the Foundation's reality was even more unpleasant &#8212; with the important difference that she was now in a position to do something about it. In the latter two cases, I got as far as the sequence where Ulrich actually dies and finds herself in the &quot;afterlife&quot;, greeted by (sirpudding's character) Operations Director Amos Sanchez and welcomed into Mobile Task Force ω-0. And in both of those cases I hit a tremendous roadblock.</p>
<p>First of all, I was exhausted. Telling someone's life story is slow and tiring. There is no such thing as a montage in prose &#8212; a single scene in a film, lasting maybe a few seconds, is a thousand words of scene-setting. And none of it was moving the real story forward in an interesting way, or commenting on it in an interesting way, which is the other valid reason for a derail.</p>
<p>Secondly, the basic fundamental concept of ω-0 is a massive can of worms. From this angle of approach, it's actually insane. You've <em>died</em> &#8212; probably under agonising and traumatic circumstances, if you're a Foundationer. And there's another plane of existence which you reach if your memories are sufficiently hardened by long-term mnestic usage? There is <em>life after death</em>? Foundationers discovered this realm, and their response to this astounding discovery was to <em>found a Mobile Task Force there</em>? I had so many follow-up questions, and so did Ulrich. Doesn't that kind of suck, the release of death followed by&#8230; years more work for the organisation you already died once serving? How do you die in this second reality, and what happens <em>then</em>? What if you <em>can't</em> die while you still have anchors, doesn't <em>that</em> suck? Who else lives on this plane, or used to? What about the Maikitian natives from <a href="/scp-2256">SCP-2256</a>, who brewed ceremonial mnestics from native flora on their islands? What about other GOIs with access to mnestic drugs, or random people with unusually strong memories? What do they do when they arrive? Do they just &quot;pass through&quot;? Or is the afterlife genuinely populated exclusively by Foundationers? If this is the noösphere, the space of all thought, what thoughts are up here? What does the landscape of human thought look like? What about exploration and science? If there's an MTF up here, shouldn't there also be a research division? Wouldn't Ulrich want to be part of that instead? What is day-to-day life up here like? Do people <em>sleep</em>? Can they even physically <em>see</em> each other?</p>
<p>It was a nightmare!</p>
<p>Addressing all of this was going to take forever, and none of it was likely to move the primary story forward. So I decided to gloss over the entire thing and leave it unaddressed, including Ulrich's backstory. It's told, not shown. Sorry. She exists. She got there somehow. She does the job I put her there to do.</p>
<p>(How can you even take a character seriously if they voluntarily joined an MTF? And then, having been killed (presumably in action), upon reaching the afterlife, <em>joined a different MTF</em>? And then was <em>killed again</em>?)</p>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Thanks to Cregan_Stark and DrAkimoto for reading drafts of this. Vast thanks to Rimple, who not only read a draft but accurately called out the problems I mentioned above, which I have, as I say, decided to leave unfixed, because I want to get past this to the good bit.</p>
<p><strong>Limitless</strong> thanks to TheMightyMcB for extremely detailed editorial critique which measurably improved almost all of these words. Also for the title, which was &quot;Z&quot; until very late in the game, and &quot;After Us, There's Nobody&quot; before that.</p>
<p>Everything good is because editors, everything bad is because I ignored editors.</p>
<p>The good news is that we are now past this. Assuming no other derails, Bart Hughes is next. I estimate we are two or three chapters from the end of <em>Five Five Five Five Five</em>.</p>
<p><em>Collapsible imposed by moderator, sorry my dude but this is a big post.</em></p>

							</div>

								
